statement.p:
Here are some examples of the correct use of the laws of exponents.


x^3 \cdot x^5 = x^8~~~~ \blert{\text{We add the exponents when multiplying.}}

(x^3)^5 = x^{15}~~~~ \blert{\text{To raise a power to a power, we multiply exponents.}}

\dfrac{x^3}{x^5} = \dfrac{1}{x^2}~~~~\blert{\text{To divide, we subtract exponents.}}

(xy)^3 = x^3y^3~~~~\blert{\text{The power of a product is the product of the powers.}}

Here are some \alert{\text{MISTAKES}} to avoid.


x^3 \cdot x^5 \not= x^{15}~~~~\blert{\text{We should add the exponents.}}

(2x)^3 \not= 2x^3~~~~\blert{\text{2 is also cubed.}}

(x+2)^3 \not= x^3+8~~~~\blert{\text{The product rule does not apply to sums.}}

2 \cdot 5^3 \not= 10^3~~~~\blert{\text{We compute powers before products.}}

solution.p:
To "undo" a square root, we square both sides of the equation. First, we isolate the square root.
    \dfrac{5 \sqrt{t}}{\alert{5}} \amp = \dfrac{83}{\alert{5}} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 5.}}

        (\sqrt{t})^2 \amp =(16.6)^2 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Square both sides.}}
        t \amp =275.56

If the variable is in the denominator of a fraction, we must first clear the fraction.
    \alert{y}(\dfrac{15}{y}) \amp = 45 \cdot \alert{y} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Multiply both sides by} ~y.}
        15 \amp = 45y \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 45.}}
        y \amp =\dfrac{15}{45}=\dfrac{1}{3}

